outputs.output:
{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you check the weather forecast and see a 70% chance of rain, meteorologists used probability to predict it. You then decide whether to bring an umbrella—that's probability thinking in action, helping you prepare for uncertainty.",
      "title": "Weather Forecasts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your insurance company uses probability to calculate premiums. They know the likelihood of accidents, health issues, or home damage based on thousands of past cases, then price your policy accordingly. You're betting against rare events.",
      "title": "Insurance Premiums"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every time you scroll past ads on social media, algorithms use probability to decide which ones you'll likely click. They've learned from millions of users which ads fit your interests—basically predicting your behavior statistically.",
      "title": "Targeted Advertising"
    },
    {
      "text": "Casino games are all probability. A slot machine's odds, a roulette wheel's outcomes, a poker hand's likelihood—casinos design games knowing the exact probability, ensuring they profit over time while players occasionally win.",
      "title": "Casino Games"
    },
    {
      "text": "Medical tests aren't perfect. A positive result doesn't mean you definitely have the condition—it depends on how likely the disease is in the general population. Doctors use probability to interpret test results and recommend next steps.",
      "title": "Medical Test Results"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you decide whether to study for a quiz last-minute versus go out, you're weighing probabilities: What's the chance I'll regret not studying versus missing out now? Probability thinking guides those real-time trade-offs.",
      "title": "Daily Decision-Making"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sports analysts predict game outcomes by analyzing player stats and past performance—essentially calculating probability. Betting odds directly show these predictions: -150 favorites, +200 underdogs. The odds reflect likelihood estimates.",
      "title": "Sports Predictions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Job interviews are probability bets. Employers choose candidates based on the likelihood they'll succeed and stay. You choose jobs based on the probable fit and growth. Both sides are making decisions under uncertainty with limited information.",
      "title": "Hiring Decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Online security uses probability. Banks flag unusual transactions based on the likelihood they're fraudulent. Your phone warns about suspicious apps based on how probable threats are. Probability protects you from rare but devastating events.",
      "title": "Fraud Detection"
    },
    {
      "text": "Netflix suggests shows you'll probably watch based on thousands of similar viewers. Spotify creates playlists using probability—if people who liked Song A also loved Song B, there's a high probability you will too.",
      "title": "Streaming Recommendations"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "It's Friday night and your favorite pizza place suddenly runs out. Demand spiked because everyone wanted pizza before the weekend, but they didn't expect the rush. Price stays same, but availability vanishes — that's supply and demand at work.",
      "title": "The Friday Night Pizza Rush"
    },
    {
      "text": "Concert tickets for your favorite artist drop. Demand is sky-high, but there are only so many seats. Prices climb fast. A few weeks before the show, unsold tickets get cheaper to fill remaining spots. Price adjusts to find the sweet spot.",
      "title": "Concert Ticket Pricing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coffee prices jumped last year because bad weather damaged coffee crops worldwide. Less supply meant fewer beans in the market. Suppliers raised prices, and some coffee drinkers switched to tea instead. Supply squeeze rippled through your morning routine.",
      "title": "When Crops Fail, Prices Rise"
    },
    {
      "text": "Black Friday deals work because stores flood the market with massive supply at rock-bottom prices. Your brain sees 'shortage' of stock and 'amazing prices' and demands surge. Stores predict this — they're deliberately manipulating both sides.",
      "title": "Black Friday Supply Explosion"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retro sneakers you love get re-released and suddenly cost way more. Supply is intentionally limited (only 500 pairs made worldwide). Demand stays high because collectors want them. Scarcity plus passion equals premium prices.",
      "title": "Limited Edition Collector Items"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gas prices spike when a hurricane threatens oil refineries. Worried demand shoots up as people panic-fill their tanks. Supply might not actually decrease much, but the fear of shortage is enough to shift the price immediately.",
      "title": "Gas Station Panic Buying"
    },
    {
      "text": "Used car prices skyrocketed during the pandemic because new car factories shut down. Supply plummeted while people stuck at home suddenly needed wheels. Demand met almost-no-supply, pushing prices to crazy levels.",
      "title": "The Used Car Shortage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your favorite restaurant adds a fancy new dish, but it's pricey because the ingredient is hard to source. Low supply keeps the price high. If it becomes popular (high demand) but stays scarce, that price won't budge.",
      "title": "Restaurant Menu Pricing Secrets"
    },
    {
      "text": "Streaming services keep raising subscription prices as demand grows and competition shrinks. Your demand for their content stays strong because you've invested time. They know you'll pay more before switching platforms.",
      "title": "Subscription Service Price Increases"
    },
    {
      "text": "Student housing near campus is crazy expensive because demand is high (thousands of students) and supply is limited (only so many apartments exist). Landlords know demand won't drop, so they raise rents yearly.",
      "title": "College Town Rent Wars"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you search your computer's folders for a file, the system dives into each folder, then searches inside folders within that folder, then folders within those — until it finds what you need. Each search is the same process, just applied to a smaller set of folders.",
      "title": "Finding Files in Nested Folders"
    },
    {
      "text": "Russian nesting dolls work recursively: open one doll and find a smaller version inside, open that and find an even smaller one, until you hit the tiniest doll that doesn't open. Each layer is the same concept, just smaller, until you reach the stopping point.",
      "title": "Russian Nesting Dolls"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you're trying to find your way out of a maze, you might explore one path, and if it branches, explore a branch within that branch. If that leads nowhere, you backtrack and try another branch at each level. You're solving the maze by recursively solving smaller maze problems.",
      "title": "Navigating a Maze"
    },
    {
      "text": "Every time you scroll through your social media feed, the app loads more posts in the same format: a profile pic, name, content, comments. Within each comment section, you see the same post structure repeated for replies to those comments. It's the same layout recursing through nested levels.",
      "title": "Social Media Comments & Replies"
    },
    {
      "text": "A company's organizational chart shows a CEO, beneath them department heads, beneath each department head are team leads, beneath each team lead are employees. Each level has the same boss-to-subordinate relationship, recurring at every rank until you hit individual contributors.",
      "title": "Corporate Hierarchy"
    },
    {
      "text": "In filmmaking, directors often use a 'shot within a shot' technique: a character watches a movie scene on TV, which contains a scene of someone watching something on their phone. The same visual pattern repeats at smaller scales, creating a recursive visual effect that feels surreal.",
      "title": "Nested Frames in Film"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you Google something, the search algorithm breaks your query into smaller components, searches for those, then combines results. If a result leads to another page with more results, it recursively applies the same searching logic to those pages.",
      "title": "Search Engine Results"
    },
    {
      "text": "In music composition, composers often use a theme, develop it into variations, and within those variations, develop smaller versions of the original theme. The musical structure echoes itself at different scales throughout the piece.",
      "title": "Musical Themes & Variations"
    },
    {
      "text": "When bacteria reproduce, each cell divides into two identical cells, which each divide into two more, which each divide again. Life replicates itself at every level — the same genetic code creating smaller versions of the original that repeat the same process.",
      "title": "Cell Division in Biology"
    },
    {
      "text": "A recipe for making soup might say: 'Make a basic broth, then add vegetables to that broth, which also gets broken into smaller cuts and cooked with the broth.' The same cooking principle (combining and breaking down) applies at each step of the recipe.",
      "title": "Cooking Complex Dishes"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Quando você está procurando um carro novo, notar que \"todo mundo\" tem aquele modelo que você quer? Você começa a vê-lo em toda parte. Isso é viés de confirmação em ação — seu cérebro destaca exemplos que confirmam sua escolha enquanto ignora os carros diferentes que passam.",
      "title": "Comprando um Carro Novo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu amigo faz um comentário sarcástico. Se vocês já tiveram conflitos antes, você interpreta como agressividade; se são próximos, vê como brincadeira. O mesmo comportamento, leitura diferente. Seu histórico com a pessoa viesa como você processa suas ações no presente.",
      "title": "Interpretando Mensagens de Amigos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Nas redes sociais, o algoritmo mostra mais conteúdo que alinha com sua visão política. Você vê todos concordando com você e pensa que a maioria da população pensa igual. Na verdade, você está em uma bolha reforçando suas próprias crenças constantemente.",
      "title": "A Bolha das Redes Sociais"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você compra um produto porque viu três influenciadores recomendando. Seu cérebro pensa \"se tantos falam bem, deve ser bom\" — ignorando que talvez milhares não recomendaram porque não tinham contrato com a marca. A frequência que você vê viesa sua percepção da realidade.",
      "title": "Confiando em Recomendações Online"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu chefe critica seu trabalho, mas você culpa as circunstâncias (faltou tempo, recursos limitados). Quando um colega faz o mesmo erro, você culpa a competência dele. Essa assimetria — atribuindo sucessos próprios à habilidade e fracassos às circunstâncias — guia suas avaliações todos os dias.",
      "title": "Avaliando Desempenho no Trabalho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu médico sugere um tratamento com 90% de chance de sucesso. Você fica entusiasmado. Se ele disser que tem 10% de chance de falhar, você fica assustado — apesar de ser exatamente a mesma informação. Como o dado é apresentado muda sua decisão sobre saúde.",
      "title": "Entendendo Estatísticas Médicas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Após um dia estressante no trabalho, você pede comida de delivery em vez de cozinhar. À noite, culpa-se por \"não ter disciplina\". Na verdade, seu cérebro cansado tomou um atalho mental que parecia eficiente no momento. Fadiga cognitiva viesa suas escolhas constantemente.",
      "title": "Decisões Quando Você Está Cansado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você vê uma notícia que confirma algo que já acreditava sobre um político e compartilha imediatamente. Semanas depois, descobre que era falsa, mas já está em seu histórico. Você tendeu a acreditar sem questionar porque se alinhava com sua visão prévia.",
      "title": "Compartilhando Notícias Políticas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Depois de assistir a um filme sobre um crime, você começa a ver perigos em toda parte — aumento de criminalidade na sua mente. A mídia amplifica certos eventos, e seu cérebro usa essa frequência como proxy para a realidade real, criando uma percepção distorcida do risco.",
      "title": "Medo Amplificado pela Mídia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você conhece alguém que confirma um estereótipo seu e pensa: \"Já sabia!\" Um contraexemplo? \"Ah, essa pessoa é exceção.\" Seu cérebro preserva a crença, ajustando a interpretação dos dados para mantê-la intacta em todas as situações.",
      "title": "Estereótipos Resistentes à Mudança"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cuando tomas antibióticos, las bacterias más resistentes sobreviven y se reproducen, creando poblaciones que los medicamentos no pueden eliminar. Es selección natural en tiempo real: los individuos 'aptos' son los que resisten el tratamiento.",
      "title": "Bacterias Resistentes en el Hospital"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las plagas de insectos evolucionan rápidamente para resistir los pesticidas que usamos. Cada generación, los insectos sensibles mueren, dejando a los resistentes para reproducirse. Vemos la selección natural ocurriendo en una sola temporada de cultivo.",
      "title": "Plagas y Pesticidas en la Granja"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los perros de distintas razas tienen características muy diferentes: pastores alemanes más grandes, chihuahuas pequeños, retriever con mayor docilidad. Los criadores seleccionaron estos rasgos durante generaciones, mostrando cómo la selección moldea poblaciones.",
      "title": "Las Razas de Perros Domesticados"
    },
    {
      "text": "En ciudades contaminadas, las polillas oscuras sobreviven mejor que las claras (predadores las ven menos en superficies negruzcas). Cuando la polución disminuyó, las polillas claras volvieron a dominar. La selección natural cambió la población en décadas.",
      "title": "Las Polillas de Manchester"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los jirafas con cuellos más largos pueden alcanzar más hojas altas en sequías severas. Sobreviven mejor y tienen más crías con cuellos largos. Con el tiempo, el cuello promedio de la población se alarga. Es selección natural esculpiendo un rasgo.",
      "title": "El Cuello de la Jirafa en Sequía"
    },
    {
      "text": "En el océano, los peces que escapan de redes de pesca son más rápidos o más pequeños. Cuando los pescadores capturan selectivamente los grandes, dejan reproducirse a los pequeños. El tamaño promedio de los peces disminuye generación tras generación.",
      "title": "La Pesca y los Peces Cada Vez Más Pequeños"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los osos polares con pelaje más denso mantienen mejor el calor en el ártico helado. Sobreviven inviernos severos que otros no resisten, dejando más descendientes con pelaje denso. La población se adapta gradualmente al frío extremo.",
      "title": "El Pelaje del Oso Polar Ártico"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando la malaria se propaga, los humanos con el rasgo genético de células falciformes tienen ventaja: resisten mejor la infección. En regiones con malaria, este rasgo (aunque causa anemia) persiste porque mejora la supervivencia reproductiva general.",
      "title": "Las Células Falciformes y la Malaria"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las flores que atraen mejor a sus polinizadores específicos (abeja, mariposa, colibrí) producen más semillas. Estos colores y formas se refuerzan generación tras generación. La selección natural ha ajustado cada flor a su polinizador particular.",
      "title": "Las Flores y Sus Polinizadores"
    },
    {
      "text": "En poblaciones de roedores, los que tienen mejor oído detectan búhos depredadores antes. Escapan más frecuentemente y tienen más crías que los que escuchan peor. El oído agudo se vuelve más común en la población con cada generación.",
      "title": "El Oído Afilado del Ratón de Campo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Every time you unlock your phone with your face, ML is comparing your features to patterns it learned from thousands of selfies you've taken. It's not following a rigid \"if nose is X pixels wide\" rule — it's recognizing the unique constellation of YOUR face.",
      "title": "Your Phone Recognizes Your Face"
    },
    {
      "text": "When Spotify suggests a song you've never heard but instantly love, that's ML finding patterns in your listening history and millions of others like you. It learns what vibe you're into, then predicts what you'll play next.",
      "title": "Your Music Playlist Gets Smarter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gmail's spam filter learns from emails you mark as junk. Over time, it recognizes sneaky patterns — certain word combinations, sender addresses, formatting tricks — without you teaching it rules. It just gets better at filtering.",
      "title": "Your Email Inbox Stays Clean"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you search for 'running shoes' once, ads follow you around the web. Advertisers use ML to predict what you might buy based on your browsing patterns, purchase history, and behavior similar to other shoppers like you.",
      "title": "Ads Know What You Want"
    },
    {
      "text": "Netflix's recommendation engine watches what you watch, when you pause, what you rewind. It learns your taste in seconds, then predicts which show will keep you binge-watching tonight versus which one you'll skip.",
      "title": "Netflix Knows Your Next Binge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your bank's fraud detection system learned from millions of transactions — both legitimate and fraudulent. Now it spots when your card is used in an unusual location or amount, flagging patterns that don't match your normal spending.",
      "title": "Your Bank Catches Fraud Instantly"
    },
    {
      "text": "When your camera app beautifies your selfie or adds portrait mode blur, ML learned from millions of face photos where skin is, where backgrounds start, and how to blur naturally. It's not applying generic rules — it's predicting what a polished version looks like.",
      "title": "Your Camera Makes You Look Better"
    },
    {
      "text": "Google's search engine predicts what you meant before you finish typing. It learned from billions of searches what queries lead to clicks and satisfaction, so it serves the most likely result first.",
      "title": "Search Completes Your Thoughts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your fitness tracker learns your patterns — when you usually run, how long you typically rest, your average heart rate. It then predicts your daily activity and alerts you if something's off, spotting patterns you wouldn't notice alone.",
      "title": "Your Fitness Tracker Knows Your Rhythm"
    },
    {
      "text": "When TikTok or Instagram's 'For You' page feels impossibly personalized, that's ML predicting which videos you'll engage with based on what millions of similar users watched. It's learning your taste in real time, second by second.",
      "title": "Social Media Predicts Your Scroll"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your $1,000 college fund sits in a savings account earning 5% annually. Year one, it grows to $1,050 from interest. Year two? You earn 5% on the full $1,050, not just the original $1,000. That extra $2.50 might seem tiny, but over decades, this \"interest earning interest\" pattern turns modest savings into serious wealth.",
      "title": "Your College Fund Growing"
    },
    {
      "text": "A friend opens a credit card with a 20% annual interest rate and carries a $5,000 balance. After one month, they owe $5,083. Month two, interest compounds on that new total. They stop using the card, but the debt keeps snowballing—not from new purchases, but from interest feeding on itself. This is compounding working against you.",
      "title": "Credit Card Debt Spiral"
    },
    {
      "text": "A 25-year-old invests $500/month in a retirement account at 8% annual returns. Another person waits 10 years, then invests $1,000/month. Despite contributing less than half the amount, the first person ends up with significantly more at retirement. Those extra years let compounding work its magic on every dollar.",
      "title": "Early Investment Advantage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bacteria in a petri dish double every 20 minutes. After an hour, you've got 8 times the original amount. After 24 hours, the colony would be incomprehensibly massive. This is compounding in nature—exponential growth that seems slow at first, then explodes. Money grows the same way, just over years instead of hours.",
      "title": "Bacterial Growth Rate"
    },
    {
      "text": "A viral TikTok starts with 100 views. After an hour, it's 500. A day later, 50,000. Views compound as people share with friends who share with their networks. Early videos grow slower; the exponential curve is gentle at first. Suddenly it's everywhere. Wealth compounds identically—slow, then unstoppable.",
      "title": "Viral Video Explosion"
    },
    {
      "text": "A mortgage lender lets you choose: pay $200,000 for a $100,000 house over 30 years, or $140,000 over 15 years. The extra payments dramatically reduce compounding interest working against you. This is why reducing loan terms saves so much money—you interrupt the compounding cycle early.",
      "title": "Mortgage Math Reality"
    },
    {
      "text": "An athlete trains hard for two years, building strength that compounds—each workout makes the next one more effective. After 5 years of consistent training, they're unrecognizable from the beginner. Talent isn't required; consistency is. Small, repeated improvements compound into extraordinary ability over time.",
      "title": "Athletic Improvement Journey"
    },
    {
      "text": "A $10,000 investment in an S&P 500 index fund grows 10% the first year—that's $1,000 gained. Year two, that $1,000 earns its own 10%, generating $100 in gains just from previous gains. By year 20, compounding generates more annual growth than your original investment ever did. Time becomes your wealth-building engine.",
      "title": "Stock Market Snowball Effect"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Toda vez que você respira ar fresco em um parque ou floresta, está aproveitando o oxigênio produzido por árvores e plantas ao seu redor. Aquele ar que enche seus pulmões? Fotossíntese em ação. Sem plantas fazendo esse trabalho constantemente, teríamos muito menos oxigênio disponível.",
      "title": "O Ar que Você Respira"
    },
    {
      "text": "A maçã do seu café da manhã, o arroz no prato, a alface da salada — tudo começa com fotossíntese. As plantas usam luz solar para fabricar glicose, que se torna o alimento que você consome. Você está, literalmente, comendo energia solar armazenada.",
      "title": "Sua Refeição Vem do Sol"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você vê uma floresta tropical exuberante ou uma plantação de cana-de-açúcar, está vendo máquinas de fotossíntese em escala gigante. Essas plantas estão constantemente absorvendo CO2 do ar e convertendo-o em biomassa — a base de toda cadeia alimentar no planeta.",
      "title": "Florestas como Fábricas de Vida"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquele alga verde brilhante em um aquário ou lagoa? Micro-organismos fotossintetizantes. Eles produzem metade do oxigênio da Terra e alimentam peixes e outras criaturas aquáticas. São como as plantas do mundo aquático, trabalhando silenciosamente.",
      "title": "Algas nos Ecossistemas Aquáticos"
    },
    {
      "text": "O aquecimento global ocorre porque queimamos combustíveis fósseis (antigos restos de plantas) e liberamos CO2. Mais fotossíntese significa mais plantas capturando esse CO2 do ar. Por isso plantações, florestas e até algas marinhas são tão importantes para equilibrar nosso clima.",
      "title": "Fotossíntese vs. Mudanças Climáticas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em estações espaciais e futuras bases lunares, os cientistas planejam usar plantas para gerar oxigênio e alimento para astronautas. Onde quer que humanos precisem sobreviver fora da Terra, levarão fotossíntese com eles — é tão essencial à vida.",
      "title": "Vida Além da Terra"
    },
    {
      "text": "Painéis solares mimetizam a fotossíntese: convertem luz em energia utilizável. Engenheiros estudam como plantas fazem isso tão eficientemente para melhorar tecnologia solar. A natureza é a melhor engenheira — e estamos aprendendo com ela.",
      "title": "Inspiração para Tecnologia Verde"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cada vez que haces una compra en línea, tu número de tarjeta viaja encriptado a través de internet. El vendedor ve tus datos reales, pero cualquiera que intente interceptar tu conexión solo vería caracteres sin sentido. La encriptación convierte tu información sensible en un idioma que solo el servidor legítimo puede entender.",
      "title": "Compras Online Seguras"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando envías un mensaje por WhatsApp o Telegram, aparece un candadito que indica que la conversación está encriptada de extremo a extremo. Ni siquiera la aplicación puede leer tus mensajes privados; solo tú y la otra persona tenéis acceso al contenido real.",
      "title": "Mensajes Privados Encriptados"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu contraseña en redes sociales nunca viaja al servidor en texto plano. Cuando inicias sesión, se encripta en tu dispositivo y llega codificada. El servidor tampoco la almacena en texto plano; la compara con una versión encriptada para verificar que es correcta.",
      "title": "Login en Redes Sociales"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando abres la banca en línea, tu navegador muestra un candadito verde. Eso significa que la encriptación está activa y tus movimientos, saldos y transferencias viajan protegidos. Un hacker en la misma red wifi que tú no podría ver nada de lo que haces.",
      "title": "Transacciones Bancarias"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tus conversaciones por email están encriptadas en tránsito hacia el servidor, así como cuando alguien las descarga. Aunque el email es menos privado que mensajería directa, la encriptación evita que alguien en la red te lea los mensajes mientras se envían.",
      "title": "Correos Electrónicos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Las apps de video llamadas como Zoom o Google Meet encriptan tu audio y video en tiempo real. Mientras hablas, todo está codificado, de modo que terceros no pueden interceptar tu conversación ni ver lo que está en tu cámara.",
      "title": "Video Llamadas Protegidas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando subes fotos a Google Drive, iCloud o Dropbox, viajan encriptadas hacia los servidores. En reposo, muchas plataformas también mantienen tus archivos encriptados, así que si alguien accediera ilegalmente a sus discos duros, tus datos seguirían siendo ininteligibles.",
      "title": "Almacenamiento en la Nube"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu teléfono inteligente almacena contraseñas guardadas, fotos privadas e información de salud de forma encriptada. Cuando desbloqueador con huella dactilar o cara, el dispositivo desencripta esos datos solo para ti, manteniéndolos invisibles para cualquiera que abra el teléfono.",
      "title": "Datos en Tu Dispositivo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando conectas tu smartwatch al teléfono, la sincronización de datos de salud, mensajes y ubicación está encriptada. Tu información de ritmo cardíaco y actividad diaria viaja codificada, no como texto legible que alguien pudiera ver si interceptara la conexión.",
      "title": "Dispositivos Inteligentes Conectados"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los podcasts y las plataformas de streaming también usan encriptación. Tu historial de reproducción, tus descargas y tus preferencias personales viajan encriptadas hacia los servidores, protegiendo tu privacidad mientras disfrutas de contenido.",
      "title": "Streaming y Podcasts"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
